<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-536-551  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 536 551.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Oct 15 1990 v16 n19 p135(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How Next makes manufacturing its quality cornerstone.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sprackland, Teri.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The state-of-the-art NeXT Computer Corp manufacturing facility inFremont, CA, employs a highly automated, fast-turnaroundproduction line that outputs 'the highest quality products at thelowest price.' NeXT claims that the $20 million,40,000-square-foot plant requires only four assembly line workers,two employees in automation, two in testing and four in finalassembly to produce $100 million worth of workstations annually.andO;High product quality rather than lowering of personnel costs isthe primary reason for the high level of automation.andP;  Otherdiscussed factors contributing to the high product quality includea highly educated manufacturing staff, employees in all operationsbeing well compensated, manufacturing viewed primarily as asoftware challenge, use of networked UNIX-based workstations withgraphical user interfaces, components being minimized, and closework with suppliers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   NeXT Inc. (Automation).andO;Topic:     WorkstationsComputer industryCase StudyManufacturersQuality controlComputer-aided manufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Keys to Next's productivity. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>